👉 Variable Arguments (VarArgs)

A function with vararg can be created in JAVA using the following syntax : 

        public static void foo(int ... arr){
            arr is available here as int [] arr
        }

foo can be called with zero or more arguments like this : 

foo(7) foo(7,8,9) foo(1,2,3,4,5,6,7) 

We can also create a function bar like this

Example : 

public class VarArgs {
    static int sum(int a , int b){
        return a+b;
    }
    static int sum(int a , int b , int c){
        return a+b;
    }
    // Using Varargs to have multiple arguments passed in the function
    static int sum(int ... arr){
        int [] a;
        int count = 0;
        for (int i=0 ; i<arr.length ; i++){
            int x = arr[i];
            count = count + x;
        }
        return count;
    }
    public static void main(String[] args){
        System.out.println("Welcome to Varargs");
        System.out.println("The sum of 4 and 5 is "+sum(4,5));
        System.out.println("The sum of 4 , 3 and 5 is "+sum(4,5 ,3));
        // No need to create these number of methods
        System.out.println("Sum of 6,5,7,4,3,2 is "+sum(6,5,7,4,3,2));
    }
}


Output :

Welcome to Varargs
The sum of 4 and 5 is 9
The sum of 4 , 3 and 5 is 9
Sum of 6,5,7,4,3,2 is 27
